{"title_page": "Lost Japan", "text_new": "{{Italic title}}\n{{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name         = Lost Japan\n| title_orig   =\n| translator   =\n| image        = Lost Japan book cover.JPG\n| image_size   = \n| caption      = 2004 edition cover\n| author       = [[Alex Kerr (Japanologist)|Alex Kerr]]\n| cover_artist =\n| country      = Japan, United States\n| language     = Japanese, English\n| series       =\n| genre        = [[History]], [[Japan]]\n| publisher    = [[Shinchosha]], Lonely Planet\n| release_date = [[1993 in literature|1993]] (Japanese), [[1996 in literature|1996]] (English)\n| media_type   = Print, e-book\n| pages        = 269 pp.\n| isbn         = 978-0-86442-370-2\n| oclc         = 951481922\n| preceded_by  = \n| followed_by  = \n}}\n{{nihongo|'''''Lost Japan'''''|\u7f8e\u3057\u304d\u65e5\u672c\u306e\u6b8b\u50cf|Utsukushiki Nihon no Zanzo}} is a 1993 book written by American Japonologist [[Alex Kerr (Japanologist)|Alex Kerr]].<ref>Komano, Tsuyoshi [http://ajw.asahi.com/article/views/opinion/AJ201311150012 INTERVIEW/ Alex Kerr: Japan needs to learn how to 'bypass' contentious issues with neighbours November 15, 2013] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151007015026/http://ajw.asahi.com/article/views/opinion/AJ201311150012 |date=October 7, 2015 }} ''[[Asahi Shimbun]]'' Retrieved October 7, 2015</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe book deals with his life in Japan and on aspects of Japanese culture that he was fascinated by. The text is a collection of Kerr's personal essays in which he suggests that the current popularity of ikebana, Kabuki, and other famous Japanese arts and crafts represents the final efflorescence of a moribund culture.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Solomon |first1=Charles |title=LOST JAPAN by Alex Kerr, translated... |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1996-10-20-bk-55694-story.html |website=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=3 February 2020 |date=20 October 1996}}</ref> He wrote it in Japanese, and it was translated into English with the help of Bodhi Fishman and published as ''Lost Japan'' in 1996.\n\nThe original Japanese version was published by Shinchosha in 1993; a paperback version has been published since 2000 by [[The Asahi Shimbun Company]]. The English translation was first published by Lonely Planet in 1996; in 2015 the book was reissued by Penguin UK with a new preface written by Alex.\n\nTranslations have also been published in Traditional and Simplified Chinese characters, Italian, Polish, Russian, and Spanish.\n\n==Reception==\nThe book won the Shincho Gakugei literature award in 1994. Kerr was the first non-Japanese winner.<ref>[http://alex-kerr.com/html/lost_japan__english_.html Alex Kerr.com - Lost Japan] Retrieved October 6, 2015</ref><ref>Kendrick, Vivienne [http://www.japantimes.co.jp/life/2006/09/09/people/alex-kerr/ Alex Kerr September 9, 2006] ''[[Japan Times]]'' Retrieved October 6, 2015</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Sokol |first1=Kathy Arlene |title=Concretizing the Japanese Dream: Alex Kerr on State-sponsored Vandals, True Romance and Contemporary Genii |url=https://kyotojournal.org/kyoto-interview/concretizing-the-japanese-dream-alex-kerr-on-state-sponsored-vandals-true-romance-and-contemporary-genii/ |website=[[Kyoto Journal]] |accessdate=3 February 2020 |date=28 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nDamian Flanagan of ''[[The Japan Times]]'' wrote, \"A fascinating chronicle of Kerr\u2019s diverse interactions with the country, the book spans such subjects as restoring a traditional Japanese house in the Iya Valley in Shikoku to collecting Japanese antiques often found languishing unloved in the kura (storehouses) of family homes. Kerr is superlative not only in bringing a connoisseur\u2019s eye to the artefacts and architecture of his adopted homeland, but also in providing revelatory insights into the country in general. He provides an illuminating exploration of many hidden, magical aspects of Japanese culture from the mandala of temples studded around Nara to the ancient brothel district of Tobita in southern Osaka.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Flanagan |first1=Damian |title=Lost Japan |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2016/01/16/books/book-reviews/lost-japan/#.Xjfy_DIzaM8 |website=[[The Japan Times]] |accessdate=3 February 2020 |date=16 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Chapters==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n#Looking for a Castle\n#[[Iya Valley]] - the author purchases and repairs [[Chiiori]]\n#[[Kabuki]] - the author describes 1977 [[Minami-za]] theatre shows and meeting then 65-year-old [[Nakamura Jakuemon IV]], an [[onnagata]] dancer\n#Art Collecting - the author describes collecting centuries-old calligraphy cheaply\n#China versus Japan\n#[[Japanese calligraphy|Calligraphy]]\n#Tenmangu (after the [[\u014csaka Tenmang\u016b Shrine]])\n#[[Trammell Crow]] - the author describes his job as an art collector for this person\n#[[Kyoto]]\n#The Road to [[Nara, Nara|Nara]]\n#Outer Nara\n#[[Osaka]]\n#The Literati - the author compares [[All Souls College, Oxford|Oxford All Souls']] Warden [[John Hanbury Angus Sparrow|John Sparrow]] as Western literati with the educated leisure class of Japan\n#Last Glimpse\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://intrepidtravelogue.com/lost-japan Review on Intrepid Travelogue]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110831071423/http://tokyoq.com/reviews/books/books_reviews/lost_japan.html Review on Tokyo Q]\n\n[[Category:Books about Japan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Italic title}}\n{{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name         = Lost Japan\n| title_orig   =\n| translator   =\n| image        = Lost Japan book cover.JPG\n| image_size   = \n| caption      = 2004 edition cover\n| author       = [[Alex Kerr (Japanologist)|Alex Kerr]]\n| cover_artist =\n| country      = Japan, United States\n| language     = Japanese, English\n| series       =\n| genre        = [[History]], [[Japan]]\n| publisher    = [[Shinchosha]], Lonely Planet\n| release_date = [[1993 in literature|1993]] (Japanese), [[1996 in literature|1996]] (English)\n| media_type   = Print, e-book\n| pages        = 269 pp.\n| isbn         = 978-0-86442-370-2\n| oclc         = 951481922\n| preceded_by  = \n| followed_by  = \n}}\n{{nihongo|'''''Lost Japan'''''|\u7f8e\u3057\u304d\u65e5\u672c\u306e\u6b8b\u50cf|Utsukushiki Nihon no Zanzo}} is a 1993 book written by American Japonologist [[Alex Kerr (Japanologist)|Alex Kerr]].<ref>Komano, Tsuyoshi [http://ajw.asahi.com/article/views/opinion/AJ201311150012 INTERVIEW/ Alex Kerr: Japan needs to learn how to 'bypass' contentious issues with neighbours November 15, 2013] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151007015026/http://ajw.asahi.com/article/views/opinion/AJ201311150012 |date=October 7, 2015 }} ''[[Asahi Shimbun]]'' Retrieved October 7, 2015</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe book deals with his life in Japan and on aspects of Japanese culture that he was fascinated by. The text is a collection of Kerr's personal essays in which he suggests that the current popularity of ikebana, Kabuki, and other famous Japanese arts and crafts represents the final efflorescence of a moribund culture.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Solomon |first1=Charles |title=LOST JAPAN by Alex Kerr, translated... |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1996-10-20-bk-55694-story.html |website=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=3 February 2020 |date=20 October 1996}}</ref> He wrote it in Japanese, and it was translated into English with the help of Bodhi Fishman and published as ''Lost Japan'' in 1996.\n\nThe original Japanese version was published by Shinchosha in 1993; a paperback version has been published since 2000 by Asahi Shuppan. The English translation was first published by Lonely Planet in 1996; in 2015 the book was reissued by Penguin UK with a new preface written by Alex.\n\nTranslations have also been published in Traditional and Simplified Chinese characters, Italian, Polish, Russian, and Spanish.\n\n==Reception==\nThe book won the Shincho Gakugei literature award in 1994. Kerr was the first non-Japanese winner.<ref>[http://alex-kerr.com/html/lost_japan__english_.html Alex Kerr.com - Lost Japan] Retrieved October 6, 2015</ref><ref>Kendrick, Vivienne [http://www.japantimes.co.jp/life/2006/09/09/people/alex-kerr/ Alex Kerr September 9, 2006] ''[[Japan Times]]'' Retrieved October 6, 2015</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Sokol |first1=Kathy Arlene |title=Concretizing the Japanese Dream: Alex Kerr on State-sponsored Vandals, True Romance and Contemporary Genii |url=https://kyotojournal.org/kyoto-interview/concretizing-the-japanese-dream-alex-kerr-on-state-sponsored-vandals-true-romance-and-contemporary-genii/ |website=[[Kyoto Journal]] |accessdate=3 February 2020 |date=28 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nDamian Flanagan of ''[[The Japan Times]]'' wrote, \"A fascinating chronicle of Kerr\u2019s diverse interactions with the country, the book spans such subjects as restoring a traditional Japanese house in the Iya Valley in Shikoku to collecting Japanese antiques often found languishing unloved in the kura (storehouses) of family homes. Kerr is superlative not only in bringing a connoisseur\u2019s eye to the artefacts and architecture of his adopted homeland, but also in providing revelatory insights into the country in general. He provides an illuminating exploration of many hidden, magical aspects of Japanese culture from the mandala of temples studded around Nara to the ancient brothel district of Tobita in southern Osaka.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Flanagan |first1=Damian |title=Lost Japan |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2016/01/16/books/book-reviews/lost-japan/#.Xjfy_DIzaM8 |website=[[The Japan Times]] |accessdate=3 February 2020 |date=16 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Chapters==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n#Looking for a Castle\n#[[Iya Valley]] - the author purchases and repairs [[Chiiori]]\n#[[Kabuki]] - the